n): variant of   Salway  ."]},{"name":"Soloway","meanings":["English: variant of   Salway  .","Americanized form of Jewish, Ukrainian, or Belorussian   Solovey   ‘nightingale’."]},{"name":"Selwyn","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire):","from the Middle English personal name <i>Selewin(e)</i> (Old English <i>Selewine</i>, perhaps from <i>sele</i> ‘hall’ or <i>sǣl</i> ‘happiness, prosperity’ + <i>wine</i> ‘friend’).","of Norman origin, perhaps from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Selvein</i>, <i>Silvein</i> (from Latin <i>Silvanus</i>, an adjective from <i>silva</i> ‘woodland’), with vocalization of /v/ to /w/, possibly through influence of the name above. In Anglo-Norman usage both <i>Selvein</i> and <i>Silvester</i> were sometimes Latinized as <i>Salvagius</i> ‘wild, savage’ (see   Sylvester   and   Savage  ), though whether the vernacular surnames were ever interchangeable is a question for further research."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Salway was born in 1300, in Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Salway, was 30 and his mother, Mrs. Richard Salway, was 25. He married Joan Mytton in 1320, in Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were 